📌 One-to-Many & Many-to-One Mapping

🔹 Concept
✅ One-to-Many (1 : N)
One entity → multiple entities
Example: User → Orders
👉 One user can have many orders

✅ Many-to-One (N : 1)
Many entities → one entity
Example: Orders → User
👉 Many orders belong to one user

🔹 Core Insight ⭐
@OneToMany  = Parent → Children
@ManyToOne  = Child → Parent

👉 They represent the same relationship from opposite sides

📌 ER Diagram (Proper)
[User] —— ◇Has◇ —— [Order]
   (1)              (N)

1 User → N Orders
1 Order → 1 User

📌 JPA Mapping

🔹 Many-to-One (MOST IMPORTANT ✅)
👉 Always the owner side
👉 Foreign key exists here
🧩 Example
@Entity
class Order {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id") // FK
    private User user;
}


🔹 One-to-Many
👉 Inverse side (usually)
🧩 Example (Bidirectional)
@Entity
class User {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user")
    private List<Order> orders;
}


🔹 Unidirectional One-to-Many (Avoid ⚠️)
@OneToMany
@JoinColumn(name = "user_id")
private List<Order> orders;

👉 Problems:
Extra updates
Less efficient
Not recommended in interviews

