📌 Many-to-Many Mapping

🔹 Concept
✅ Many-to-Many (N : N)
Many entities relate to many other entities
👉 Example:
Student ↔ Course
One student can enroll in many courses
One course can have many students

🔹 Core Idea ⭐
Many ↔ Many = Requires a JOIN TABLE

👉 Direct FK cannot handle this
👉 So we use a third table (junction table)

📌 ER Diagram
[Student] —— ◇Enrolls◇ —— [Course]
    (N)                    (N)


🔹 With Join Table (Important)
Student_Course
+------------+------------+
| student_id | course_id  |
+------------+------------+


📌 JPA Mapping

🔹 Owning Side (IMPORTANT ⭐)
👉 Only one side is owner
@Entity
class Student {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToMany
    @JoinTable(
        name = "student_course",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
    )
    private List<Course> courses;
}


🔹 Inverse Side
@Entity
class Course {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "courses")
    private List<Student> students;
}


📌 Key Annotations
Annotation
Purpose
@ManyToMany
Defines relationship
@JoinTable
Defines join table
joinColumns
FK of owner
inverseJoinColumns
FK of other side
mappedBy
Inverse side


📌 Ownership Rule ⭐
Owner = side with @JoinTable

Controls insertion into join table
Only one owner allowed

📌 Fetch Type
Mapping
Default
@ManyToMany
LAZY ✅


📌 Cascade
@ManyToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL)

⚠️ Be careful:
REMOVE can delete unintended data

